Troubleshooting Tips
Issue: No packets captured in PCAP file

Solution: Ensure server and client are running during capture
Verify correct interface (use lo for localhost traffic)
Check tcpdump has proper permissions (use sudo)
Issue: Scapy import errors

Solution: Install Scapy with pip3 install scapy
May need to install libpcap-dev: sudo apt-get install libpcap-dev
Issue: Cannot parse protocol fields correctly

Solution: Verify byte order (big-endian vs little-endian)
Check struct format strings match protocol specification
Use hex dumps to manually verify field positions
Issue: Server crashes during fuzzing

Solution: This may indicate a vulnerability - document the crash case
Implement proper error handling in server code
Use try-except blocks to catch parsing errors
Conclusion
This lab demonstrated practical reverse engineering techniques for undocumented network protocols. You learned to capture traffic, identify protocol structure through pattern analysis, detect security vulnerabilities, and automate analysis using Python and Scapy. These skills are essential for security researchers analyzing proprietary protocols, IoT devices, and custom network applications.

Key takeaways:

Protocol reverse engineering requires systematic analysis of traffic patterns
Security vulnerabilities often exist in custom protocols due to lack of peer review
Automation tools significantly improve analysis efficiency
Proper documentation is crucial for understanding protocol behavior
Always obtain authorization before testing real-world systems
Continue practicing these techniques on CTF challenges and authorized penetration testing engagements to develop expertise in protocol analysis and security assessment.
